Review: SQL

SQL stands for Structured Query Language
Standard way to manipulate databases
Categorized into: DDL, DML, DCL

Review: Data Modeling

DDL: Create, Alter, Drop database Structure/Schema
DML: Select, Insert, Update, Delete Data
DCL: Grant and Revoke Access

Remember...

How Relational Database get it's name?
Relationship between tables
So we can resolve values in other tables by "JOINing related TABLES"

Type of JOIN

INNER JOIN
LEFT JOIN
RIGHT JOIN
SELF JOIN
CROSS JOIN

INNER JOIN

Returns only records that have matching values in both tables.

LEFT JOIN

Returns all records in left table, and matching records in right table.

RIGHT JOIN

Returns all records in right table, and matching records in left table.

SELF JOIN

Similar with inner join, but left and right tables are same table.

CROSS JOIN

Returns all combinations between left and right tables

INNER JOIN

Template
              
                SELECT a.col1, b.col1 
                FROM table_a AS a 
                INNER JOIN table_b AS b ON b.fk = a.pk 
                WHERE [additional clause]
Example
              
                SELECT a.name, b.name 
                FROM country AS a
                INNER JOIN city AS b ON b.country_id = a.id 
                WHERE c.continent = 'Asia'

LEFT JOIN

Template
              
                SELECT a.col1, b.col1 
                FROM table_a AS a 
                LEFT JOIN table_b AS b ON b.fk = a.pk 
                WHERE [additional clause]
Example
              
                SELECT a.name, b.name 
                FROM country AS a
                LEFT JOIN city AS b ON b.country_id = a.id 
                WHERE c.continent = 'Asia'

RIGHT JOIN

Template
              
                SELECT a.col1, b.col1 
                FROM table_a AS a 
                RIGHT JOIN table_b AS b ON b.fk = a.pk 
                WHERE [additional clause]
Example
              
                SELECT a.name, b.name 
                FROM country AS a
                RIGHT JOIN city AS b ON b.country_id = a.id 
                WHERE c.continent = 'Asia'

CROSS JOIN

Template
              
                SELECT a.col1, b.col1 
                FROM table_a AS a 
                CROSS JOIN table_b AS b ON b.fk = a.pk 
                WHERE [additional clause]
Example
              
                SELECT a.name, b.name 
                FROM country AS a
                CROSS JOIN city AS b ON b.country_id = a.id 
                WHERE c.continent = 'Asia'

Aggregate

Like Create Pivot Table
COUNT
SUM
MIN and MAX
AVG

COUNT

Count number of records in selected column
Count ALL Columns
              
                SELECT COUNT(*) AS table_a
Count Single Column
              
                SELECT COUNT(high) AS table_a
NOTE: Count threat NULL cell as NA

SUM

Summarize all values in selected column
Sum Single Column
              
                SELECT SUM(salary) AS table_a
NOTE: Sum threat NULL cell as 0

Min and Max

Min returns lowest number, earliest date, or non-numerical value as close alphabetically to "A" as possible
Max returns the highest number, the latest date, or the non-numerical value closest alphabetically to "Z"
Min Single Column
              
                SELECT Min(salary) AS table_a
Max Single Column
              
                SELECT MAX(salary) AS table_a

AVG

Calculates the average of values in selected column
AVG Single Column
              
                SELECT AVG(salary) AS table_a
NOTE: AVG ignore NULL completely

GROUP BY

COUNT, AVG, SUM aggregate entire table
GROUP BY: Separate data into groups
GROUP BY: Aggregate for each group
NOTE: columns used in GROUP BY, must appear in SELECT clause

GROUP BY

              
                SELECT year, COUNT(*) AS count
                FROM stock_price
                GROUP BY year
              
            
              
                SELECT year, month, COUNT(*) AS count
                FROM stock_price
                GROUP BY year, month

GROUP BY ORDER BY

Sorting the result by selected columns
Columns must be appeared in the PIVOT TABLE not in the DATA
              
                SELECT year, month, COUNT(*) AS count
                FROM stock_price
                GROUP BY year, month
                ORDER BY year, month

GROUP BY HAVING

Filtering the result of aggregated table
              
                SELECT year,
                  month,
                  MAX(high) AS month_high
                FROM stock_price
                GROUP BY year, month
                HAVING MAX(high) > 400
                ORDER BY year, month

GROUP BY HAVING

Alternatively might use SUBQUERY
              
                SELECT * FROM (
                  SELECT year,
                    month,
                    MAX(high) AS month_high
                  FROM stock_price
                  GROUP BY year, month
                ) AS stock_price
                WHERE month_high > 400
                ORDER BY year, month

NORMALIZATION

MAIN PURPOSE: Avoid Redundancy
- Wastage Storage
- Data integrity
- Faster Query (by Applying Index)

DATA ANOMALY

Unexpected side effect of trying to insert, update, or delete a row

DATA ANOMALY

Insert new retail with no stock in it, will result null in stock
Delete stock ID (i.e. I1106), will also delete stock
Update retail ID (i.e. 1001), will update multiple rows having same retail ID

1ST NORMAL FORM

All the attributes of R are atomic
No Multi-Value Attributes

2ST NORMAL FORM

1ST NF Already
No partial dependency in R between non-key attributes and key attributes

3ST NORMAL FORM

2ST NF Already
No transitive dependency that exists between key attributes and non-key attributes through other non-key attributes
- The class of an Item depends on the price
- The age depends on date of birth
